<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12105c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12105c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12105c"> 105(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>roast<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> pigs in street run ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Ils firent de belles noces: il y a avait des barriques &agrave; tous les coins de rues, des cochons r&ocirc;tis qui couraient par les rues avec la fourchette sur le dos, du poivre et du sel dans les oreilles et la moutarde sous la queue, et qui en voulait, coupait un morceau. J&apos;&eacute;tais charg&eacute; de faire la sauce, mais j&apos;eus la sottise d&apos;y go&ucirc;ter et l&apos;on me mit dehors; alors je m&apos;en allai par sur le pont de Gan&eacute;dic, et voil&agrave; le conte fini. <br><font color="green">[They had a wonderful wedding: there were barrels at every corner of the street, <mark>roasted pigs ran in the street</mark> with forks in their back, salt and pepper in their ears and mustard under their tails, and everybody who wanted, could slice off a piece. I was responsible for the sauce, but I made the mistake of tasting it and I was kicked outside; so I went to the bridge of Gan&eacute;dic and that is the end of my tale.]</font> <small> <a name="RDTP2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RDTP2"><cite title="source">Revue des Traditions Populaires</cite></a> (1902) 242-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Traditional ending of Breton fairy tale. Source may be other than cited. </mm> </dd></dl>
